This is a minimal example project using libcwd.

This example project uses gitache to fetch libcwd from github, so there
is no need to have it installed.

If you have a local install and want to use that, then comment out the
gitache block in CMakeLists.txt. And in that case, if libcwd was installed
with an uncommon prefix then CMake can still find it if you add
`<install_prefix>/lib/cmake/libcwd` to CMAKE_PREFIX_PATH.

Note: The directories cmake/aicxx/ and cwds/ in this example project the git submodules
https://github.com/CarloWood/cmake-aicxx and
https://github.com/CarloWood/cwds
You will have to add those as submodules to your project as well.


To configure and build the example project run:

    cmake -S . -B build -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Debug -DExampleOption=ON
    cmake --build build --parallel --verbose

Note that a Release build will not show the ExampleOption,
which is due to the fact that it uses `"CW_BUILD_TYPE_IS_NOT_RELEASE" OFF`
in the CMakeLists.txt file.


Then run the example with:

    LIBCWD_RCFILE_OVERRIDE_NAME=libcwdrc_example-project build/src/helloworld

Note: You can also not set LIBCWD_RCFILE_OVERRIDE_NAME in which case libcwd will
use your ~/.libcwdrc and probably not show the CUSTOM debug channel output
unless you turn that on in that file first.
